				"uid" : {
					"__type" : "uid",
					"uidString" : "lPJGxYrzDQC8VQ8WBRKL7w=="
				},
				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "if you base your business plan on the statistical averages of business plans, you won’t come up with a good company that is able to innovate and execute. if you build your software application on the statistical average of software applications, you’ll get slop, because most software is slop. and, as we have by now mostly agreed (thank god), if you create a picture based on the statistical average of pictures, you don’t get art. you still get a sensible-looking, middle of the road system. but if you value your work and the work of the professionals working in the fields you are currently automating, then you know that’s not good enough.\n\nand i think that’s why everyone wants to automate everyone else’s work but not their own. because they know enough about their own field to think or even know that they are not so easily replacable, that there is nuance and taste and the quality without a name (TM: christopher alexander) involved. but if you look at work you’re not familiar with, you don’t have this nuance. you don’t have taste. you are an idiot in any field you haven’t explored deeply, and that’s when you think it would be easy to automate the work you don’t know how to do. it sounds stupid because it is stupid, but it’s also a deeply human thing to think."
			},
