					"uidString" : "nFWtgYrzDQCxSGfIBRKL7w=="
				},
				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "So, where does this disconnect between how people (in my opinion) *should* work with LLMs, and how they actually *do*?"
			},
			{
				"__type" : "textSnippet",
				"children" : {
					"__type" : "snippets",
					"items" : [ ]
				},
				"createEmail" : {
					"__type" : "email",
					"emailString" : "<unknown>"
				},
				"createTime" : {
					"__type" : "time",
					"time" : {
						"__type" : "dateAndTime",
						"dateAndTimeString" : "2025-06-09T21:41:24.287851+02:00"
					}
				},
				"editEmail" : {
					"__type" : "email",
					"emailString" : "<unknown>"
				},
				"editTime" : {
					"__type" : "time",
					"time" : {
						"__type" : "dateAndTime",
						"dateAndTimeString" : "2025-06-09T23:25:24.009009+02:00"
					}
				},
				"uid" : {
					"__type" : "uid",
					"uidString" : "PH2t/HLyDQCnAj/hCBR5Zw=="
				},
				"paragraphStyle" : {
					"__type" : "textStyle"
				},
				"string" : "I believe most of the mismatch comes from a great hyperstition, and where people sit in the big cult chamber of the LLM. Those that are “in the know” tend to perceive the current state as a given, and talk of LLMs in terms of their value accretion potential, its paradigms, and the things it could fundamentally enable—even if it currently sucks at them. Those that are “outsiders” cannot easily distinguish between what works and what doesn’t, and take the hyperstituous, futuristic aspect of the technology as its current state<sup><a href=\"1\">1.</a></sup>. It doesn’t help that we mix tech and product demos into a pasty slop that requires us to test every feature we see online to know whether it truly works as advertised or not."
			},
			{
				"__type" : "textSnippet",
				"children" : {
					"__type" : "snippets",
					"items" : [ ]
